# Analyzing the performance and fairness of BBRv3 against prior iterations as well as other CC algorithms

**Introduction**  
Congestion control, which is mainly used in TCP, manages the rate at which data packets are sent out of a program in order to maximize throughput, minimize packet loss, and respond in the presence of congestion. As a result of the decentralized nature of the internet \- since designers chose to forgo the idea of reliable reserved circuits in favor of packet switching \- users individually must control the rate at which they send out packets while considering the congestion on the network that other people cause, as well as the multiple flows that run concurrently on their own computer and network.  
Although the bandwidth of the internet has increased over the years, with direct fiber to the premises being more widespread, it has not correlated with a direct increase in transmission rates because of increased congestion, bottlenecks in the network, and bufferbloat to name a few things. The need for good congestion control algorithms has never been higher. Algorithms such as TCP Cubic or TCP Reno use packet loss as the primary indicator of congestion while BBR uses bottleneck bandwidth and round trip time (RTT) as indicators of congestion. These metrics directly affect the size of its congestion window or rate of packet transmission. Either approach to measure congestion has its strengths and weaknesses, but regardless of the algorithm that you choose, compromises will be made.  
Loss-based approaches like TCP Cubic have high bandwidth utilization and share bandwidth quite fairly, but are very susceptible to random losses which are common in wireless networks. This is a massive blow because of the high utilization of protocols like wifi and cellular. Google’s BBR protocol, on the other hand, uses a rate-driven approach that constantly probes the network for the RTT and available bandwidth, while ignoring packet loss altogether. This approach is less reactive to spikes in congestion, but allows for very high bandwidth utilization while being resilient to random losses.  
BBRv2 and then BBRv3 was then later introduced by Google which improved upon BBR by improving bandwidth sharing across flows and incorporating packet loss into the congestion algorithm to prevent excessive losses.  
	This paper analyzes BBRv3 as well as 5 other congestion control algorithms, including the original BBR algorithm, and evaluates their throughput and fairness in the face of multiple flows of the same congestion control algorithm as well as different algorithms. Since we implement a virtual network environment for these flows, we have full control over the scenarios that they run under.

**Problem Statement**  
	Google’s BBR was very popular when it was first introduced in 2016\. Google has so much confidence in their congestion control algorithm that they have replaced Cubic with BBR for all TCP flows on their WAN that connects their data centers. BBRv1 also comes included with the Linux kernel as a usable congestion control algorithm along with TCP Cubic and TCP Reno. Now that we have so many congestion control algorithms to choose from, we need to evaluate and measure which congestion control algorithm is exactly the best and most fair to other flows.  
	The aim of a congestion control algorithm is to have the most throughput, that is, to have the most data that is able to safely make it across the internet from its sender to its receiver. The routing infrastructure between these two endpoints is the challenge that congestion control algorithms face, which hampers their ability to safely transmit data. Packets can be lost seemingly randomly or dropped by routers themselves if their buffers are full.  
	We want to measure the throughput of each congestion control algorithm, considering time and also in the presence of congestion in the form of multiple concurrent flows. We will also visually plot these points of data to see any trends or interesting kinks that might occur while these algorithms operate. Finally, we will determine whether or not BBRv3 is worth installing and using, or if another congestion control algorithm is better.

**Approach**  
	To solve this problem, we decided that creating a controlled virtual network of virtual machines is better than testing across the Internet. This is because we can have direct control of what flows we inject into the network and give each congestion control algorithm a fair chance at its best performance, since the Internet is public and unpredictable. Using a virtual network also allows us to map out the exact network topography and have direct control over the size of the buffers on the routers. This is crucial because it allows us to understand the data that we observe and draw conclusions on why certain behaviors happen.

**Solution**  
	We set up a dumbbell-topology network where half of the network contains senders and the other half of the network contains receivers. The senders and receivers are separated and connected by 2 routers, one that belongs to the senders and the other that belongs to the receivers. These routers act as network bottlenecks for the flow of data and we can very easily overwhelm these routers, especially when multiple concurrent flows exist in the network.  
	We run 3 different tests to evaluate the effectiveness of each congestion control algorithm. First, we run individual tests on all 6 congestion control algorithms while observing their throughput over time, round trip time, and congestion window size. Next, we run 3 concurrent flows of each congestion control algorithm. This test would tell us how fair each algorithm is and allows us to compare their throughputs while we control the size of the buffer and the RTT delay. Finally, we run a test where all 6 algorithms are active and sending concurrent flows. This will be our stress test, and we hope that a clear winner with the highest throughput and fairness will emerge from the competition. We hypothesize that BBRv3 will not perform much better than its predecessors, but may be more fair. We believe PCC will perform better in the stress test due to being a loss-based CC, but it could still suffer high queuing delays due to no bound on in-flight data.

**Conclusion**  
	Congestion control algorithms are imperative to efficient use of networks. Whether it's a controlled environment like inside a datacenter or on the internet, choosing the correct congestion control algorithm can massively speed up every operation that you make. We thought initially that BBRv3 would not perform better than its predecessor BBRv1. In order to test this hypothesis, we created a dumbbell network with senders and receivers on opposite ends of two routers. Using this setup, we observe that Google’s BBRv3 definitely is not better than BBR or many other congestion control algorithms based on the data and the findings that resulted from them. In fact, based on the many tests that we ran, PCC seems to have come out on top of the competition, especially the loss-based algorithms. We see that individually, they all are able to get around 34-38Mbps throughput, but once put to a stress test, the loss-based algorithms started entering congestion avoidance mode while the algorithms that do not rely on them made better use of the extra bandwidth and saw increases in throughput. BBRv3, however does shine in throughput with variable buffer sizes. It was the most fair across its 3 senders of the congestion control algorithms while having the highest throughput numbers.
